{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"3bec41d5-1379-4720-b9b7-5e3c7a4bfa3a","content":"The project doesn't exist yet, so here's what you need to configure in your `.csproj` to publish as a **dotnet tool** on NuGet.org:\n\n### Required `.csproj` properties\n\n```xml\n<PropertyGroup>\n  <OutputType>Exe</OutputType>\n  <TargetFramework>net8.0</TargetFramework>\n\n  <!-- Makes this a dotnet tool -->\n  <PackAsTool>true</PackAsTool>\n  <ToolCommandName>my-mcp-server</ToolCommandName>\n\n  <!-- NuGet metadata -->\n  <PackageId>MyMcpServer</PackageId>\n  <Version>1.0.0</Version>\n  <Authors>YourName</Authors>\n  <Description>An MCP server for ...</Description>\n  <PackageProjectUrl>https://github.com/you/repo</PackageProjectUrl>\n  <PackageLicenseExpression>MIT</PackageLicenseExpression>\n  <PackageReadmeFile>README.md</PackageReadmeFile>\n</PropertyGroup>\n```\n\n### Key points\n\n1. **`PackAsTool=true`** — tells `dotnet pack` to produce a tool package.\n2. **`ToolCommandName`** — the CLI command users will run (e.g., `my-mcp-server`).\n3. **`OutputType=Exe`** — required; tools must be executables.\n\n### Publish steps\n\n```bash\n# Pack\ndotnet pack -c Release\n\n# Push to NuGet.org (get your API key from nuget.org/account/apikeys)\ndotnet nuget push bin/Release/MyMcpServer.1.0.0.nupkg \\\n  --api-key YOUR_API_KEY \\\n  --source https://api.nuget.org/v3/index.json\n```\n\n### Users install & run with\n\n```bash\ndotnet tool install -g MyMcpServer\nmy-mcp-server          # runs via stdio\n```\n\nThat's all that's needed — no custom packaging or entry-point wiring required.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"0a32dc00-759c-4590-87ce-4ac2b1a97e23","outputTokens":508,"requestId":"CBC2:D88B:1835D3C:1B7B914:69FE899E"},"id":"d814adb1-f3fe-4275-95d4-431b9461b08b","timestamp":"2026-05-09T01:11:03.907Z","parentId":"297741c5-fdc5-404e-b892-1971a2316b6c"}
